# Public Prosecutor _v_ Kong Wei Keong Marcus  

### \[2022\] SGMC 48

Criminal Law – Offences – Penal Code – Computer Misuse and Cybersecurity Act

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9095/2022/01.\]

24 August 2022

### District Judge Teo Guan Kee:

## Introduction

1       Kong Wei Keong, Marcus, the **Accused**, claimed trial to 54 charges (the “**Charges**”) comprising:

> (a)     32 charges under section 379 of the Penal Code (Cap 224, 2008 Rev Ed, “**PC**”);

> (b)     21 charges under section 3(1) of the Computer Misuse and Cybersecurity Act (Cap 50A, 2007 Rev Ed, “**CMA**”); and

> (c)     1 charge under section 182 of the PC (subsequently amended to one under section 203 of the PC).

2       Following the trial of this matter, I found the Accused guilty and convicted him on 53 of the Charges. The Accused was granted a discharge amounting to acquittal on one Charge (MAC-903074-2017, the 53rd Charge). I sentenced the Accused to a global term of 17 months and 8 weeks’ imprisonment. The sentence imposed for each Charge is set out in the table annexed to these Grounds.

3       The Accused, being dissatisfied with his conviction and sentence, has filed an appeal. He is currently on bail pending the hearing of this appeal.

## Background

4       By way of background, in or around May 2015, the Accused and one Lee Yen Pheng, Felicia (the “**Victim**”) were in a romantic relationship. It was also around this time that the Accused moved into the Victim’s residence. He resided with the Victim until sometime in or around February 2016.

5       All but one of the Charges brought against the Accused allege that, during the period when he was residing with the Victim, he committed various property-related offences in relation to the financial assets of the Victim. The remaining Charge alleges that the Accused gave false information to the police when the Victim discovered the loss of some of her financial assets and made a police report regarding the same.

## The Charges

6       The Charges fall broadly into four categories.

### Stolen Card Charges

7       The Accused faced five Charges (the “**Stolen Card Charges**”) under section 379 of the PC for stealing credit cards or ATM cards belonging to the Victim. These were the subject matter of the 49th to 53rd Charges brought against the Accused.

8       As the Charges in question are worded in similar fashion, I reproduce below the terms of the 49th Charge:

> You, \[particulars of the Accused\] are charged that you, sometime in July 2015, at \[address of the Victim\], did commit theft of one POSB ATM card in the name of \[the Victim\], in the possession of \[the Victim\], and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 379 of the Penal Code, Chapter 224.

9       The cards (the “**Stolen Cards**”) which the Accused is said to have misappropriated were:

> (a)     49th Charge: One POSB ATM card (the “**POSB Card**”);

> (b)     50th Charge: One Citi SMRT Platinum VISA credit card (the “**Citi Card**”);

> (c)     51st Charge: One DBS Live Fresh VISA credit card (the “**DBS Card**”);

> (d)     52nd Charge: One UOB Lady’s Classic Master card (the “**UOB Lady’s Card**”); and

> (e)     53rd Charge: One UOB Cashplus card (the “**UOB Cashplus Card**”).

### Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges

10     It was alleged that, having misappropriated the Stolen Cards, the Accused used them to, _inter alia_, make unauthorised cash withdrawals from ATM machines, such withdrawals amounting to theft under Section 379 of the PC.

11     The Accused faced 27 Charges (the “**Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges**”) of making the aforementioned unauthorised withdrawals from various accounts maintained by the Victim with various financial institutions between 23 June 2015 and 7 August 2015. Details of the amount involved in each Unauthorised Withdrawal Charge are set out in the table annexed to these Grounds. One such Charge (the 1st Charge) is set out below by way of illustration:

> You, \[particulars of the Accused\] are charged that you, on the 29th day of June 2015, at a Citibank Automated Teller Machine, in Singapore, did commit theft of cash amounting to S$3,000.00, to wit, by making an Automated Teller Machine withdrawal using a CITI SMRT Platinum VISA card in the name of \[the Victim\] bearing serial number \[card number\], in the possession of Citibank Singapore Ltd and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 379 of the Penal Code, Chapter 224.

12     The unauthorised withdrawals which are the subject of the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges were made from the following accounts belonging to the Victim, with the number of Charges pertaining to each account set out beside the account identified:

> (a)     the account associated with the Citi Card (6 Charges);

> (b)     the account associated with the DBS Card (10 Charges);

> (c)     the account associated with the UOB Lady’s Card (10 Charges); and

> (d)     One POSB Savings account belonging to the Victim, using the POSB Card (1 Charge).

### Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges

13     Apart from the Charges pertaining to the theft of the Victim’s funds, the Accused faced 21 Charges under the CMA (the “**Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges**”). These alleged that the Accused, without authority, accessed the Victim’s bank or credit card accounts and performed fund transfers from the accounts in question to his own account or to the Victim’s account associated with the UOB Lady’s Card. Two such Charges, one involving a transfer to the Victim’s credit card account and another involving a transfer to the Accused’s account, are set out below by way of illustration:

> 28th Charge

> You, \[particulars of the Accused\] are charged that you on the 15th day of July 2015, in Singapore, did knowingly cause a computer to perform a function for the purpose of securing access without authority to a program held in a computer, to wit, by accessing the United Overseas Bank iBanking network, which you were not authorised to access, using one Lee Yen Pheng Felicia UOB Cash Plus account bearing account number \[account number\], to make a fund transfer of S$5,000.00 for a credit card payment, and you have thereby committed an offence under Section 3(1) of the Computer Misuse and Cybersecurity Act, Chapter 50A, 2007 Rev Ed.

> 40th Charge

> You, \[particulars of the Accused\] are charged that you on the 1st day of August 2015, in Singapore, did knowingly cause a computer to perform a function for the purpose of securing access without authority to a program held in a computer, to wit, by accessing the DBS iBanking network, which you were not authorised to access, using one Lee Yen Pheng Felicia POSB Saving account bearing account number \[account number\], to make a fund transfer of S$2,500.00 to your POSB Saving account bearing \[account number\], and you have thereby committed an offence under Section 3(1) of the Computer Misuse and Cybersecurity Act, Chapter 50A, 2007 Rev Ed.

14     The unauthorised fund transfers were made by the Accused from the following accounts belonging to the Victim:

> (a)     the account associated with the DBS Card (1 Charge);

> (b)     the account associated with the UOB Cashplus Card (the “**UOB Cashplus Account**”, 11 Charges); and

> (c)     two of the Victim’s POSB Savings accounts (9 Charges).

### False Information Charge

15     The 54th Charge brought against the Accused pertained to information which he provided to the police on 17 August 2015.

16     On this date, both the Victim and the Accused made police reports pertaining to the Victim’s bank accounts. It is alleged that the police report made by the Accused contained information which the Accused knew to be false.

17     As will be further elaborated on below, the Prosecution originally proceeded under section 182 of the PC in relation to this Charge but, at the stage of making closing submissions following the close of the case for the Defence and following an invitation by the court, made an application for the Charge to be amended to one under section 203 of the PC.

18     The amended **False Information Charge** states:

> You, \[particulars of Accused\], are charged that you, on 17 August 2015, in Singapore, having reason to believe that an offence under section 3(1) of the Computer Misuse and Cybersecurity Act (Cap. 50A) has been committed, namely, you accessed \[the Victim’s\] DBS iBanking network without authority to transfer monies from Felicia’s POSB saving account nos. \[number\] and \[number\] to your POSB savings account no. \[number\] between 1 August 2015 and 16 August 2015, gave false information respecting that offence which you knew was false, to wit, you gave the police information that you had no idea how money was being transferred from Felicia’s bank account into your bank account, and you have thereby committed an offence under section 203 of the Penal Code (Cap. 224, Rev. Ed. 2008).

## Witnesses Called

19     The following witnesses gave evidence on behalf of the Prosecution:

> (a)     the Victim;

> (b)     ASP Ng Yong Da Justin;

> (c)     Siti Faizah binte Abdullah;

> (d)     Inspector Mohamad Shahudin bin Abu Bakar; and

> (e)     Station Inspector Tan Jun Sheng Robin.

20     Apart from the Victim herself, the other four witnesses were serving or former police officers who were involved in investigating the Charges or, in the case of Station Inspector Tan Jun Sheng Robin, who recorded the police report that forms the subject matter of the False Information Charge.

21     The Accused was the only witness to give evidence on behalf of the Defence.

## Summary of the Prosecution and Defence Cases

22     In summary, the Prosecution’s case against the Accused is that:

> (a)     He misappropriated the Stolen Cards from the Victim (the subject of the Stolen Card Charges) and used them to either make cash withdrawals from ATMs (the subject of the unauthorised Withdrawal Charges) or to make unauthorised fund transfers (the subject of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges) using the Victim’s banking facilities.

> (b)     Thereafter, when the Victim made a police report upon discovering unauthorised transactions made using her bank accounts, the Accused allegedly chose to falsely claim that he knew nothing of the aforementioned transactions, which he had in fact carried out.

23     On his part, the Accused’s primary defence in these proceedings was that he was at all material times authorised by the Victim to use her ATM and credit cards to carry out the transactions which were the subject matter of the Charges. He asserted that there was, or he believed that there was, an agreement (the “**Agreement**”) between the Victim and himself conferring upon him the authority to use the Victim’s credit cards and ATM cards such that his possession of the Victim’s credit cards and ATM cards, as well as his acts of carrying out the transactions which are the subject matter of all the Charges apart from the False Information Charge, could not be said to have been carried out without the Victim’s consent or dishonestly.

24     The existence of the Agreement was roundly denied by the Victim.

25     Given that the existence of the Agreement forms the primary plank of the Accused’s defence to most of the Charges brought against him, I will begin by considering whether there was evidence to support the existence of such an Agreement.

## Existence of an Agreement between the Accused and the Victim

### The Accused’s submissions

26     The scope of the Agreement was cast in very wide terms by the Accused, and was said to have conferred upon the Accused an unfettered discretion to use the Victim’s financial resources as he wished, regardless of the amount involved, particularly if it was for the Victim’s benefit.

27     The Accused relied on a number of matters as establishing the existence of the Agreement. In summary, these are:

> (a)     The Accused had access to the Victim’s wallet and mobile telephone.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1)

> (b)     The Accused made payments to and on behalf of the Victim from his own money.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2)

> (c)     The Accused made payments between the Victim’s own accounts with her authorisation.[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3)

> (d)     The Victim made only a few transactions on her own.[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4)

> (e)     The Accused and the Victim were in a close romantic relationship at the time of the offences.[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5)

28     For the reasons I set out below, I was not satisfied that the foregoing was sufficient to support the existence of the Agreement, or alternatively, of the Accused’s belief in one.

#### Access to the Victim’s wallet and mobile phone.

29     At the trial, the Victim confirmed that she began a romantic relationship with the Accused in or around May 2015, and allowed him to live with her as he had offered to take care of her. The Victim, at the time, suffered from what she said was a severe eczema condition.

30     The Victim testified that during the period when the Accused resided with her, he had access to the Victim’s mobile phone, laptops, house key and letter box key:

> Q    Ms. Lee, when Marcus was staying with you at your house, what items around the house did he have access to?

> A    He have access to my handphone, laptops, house key, letterbox key. [\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6)

31     It was apparent that whilst the Victim used the word “access” in her testimony, she did not intend for that term to carry any connotation of consent or acquiescence. She was simply stating that the Accused had the opportunity, _inter alia_, to gain physical access to her wallet as the Accused was staying with the Victim at the time.

32     I accept that there is some evidence that the Victim did on occasion permit the Accused to take cash from her wallet.

33     In an online exchange in October 2015,[\[note: 7\]](#Ftn_7) the Accused informed the Victim that he had taken a sum of $20 from the Victim’s wallet and the Victim did not object to this.

34     This does not, however, in my view necessarily support the much wider-ranging Agreement submitted for by the Accused, particularly when the amount which he is alleged to have misappropriated is much larger than $20.

35     In the aforementioned October 2015 exchange, the Accused, despite taking a relatively modest sum of $20, had started the exchange by stating “Sorry I also forget to first thing account to you how much I took last night”. After informing the Victim that he had taken $20 from her wallet, he was told by the Victim that “We need to spend slower”. In response, the Accused promised to “let \[the Victim\] know how much I spent buying all the stuff” and also stated that “I am already buying all the cheapest thing I can buy already”.

36     Contrary to the existence of any Agreement, this exchange shows, first, that the Victim expected to be informed by the Accused when he helped himself to her funds and, secondly, that the Victim was careful with her spending.

37     As for access to the Victim’s mobile phone, the Accused relied on another exchange between himself and the Victim, recorded in exhibit D25, wherein the Victim chastised the Accused for having “misuse my trust in giving you free access to my phone”.

38     It is not apparent how this exchange supports the existence of the Agreement. The reference to “free access” is followed by an allegation that the Accused had, in apparent abuse of the trust reposed in him by the Victim, sent conversations between the Victim and third parties to his own email without permission. There is thus no suggestion that the term “free access” in this context encompassed access by the Accused to the Victim’s credit card, bank accounts or to the Victim’s mobile phone for the purpose of making or facilitating banking transactions.

#### Payments made by the Accused to the Victim.

39     The Accused submitted that the existence of the Agreement was also supported by the fact that he was not exclusively withdrawing moneys from the Victim’s accounts; there were occasions on which he made payments or transfers of funds to the Victim as well.

40     Most of the payments which the Accused claims to have been made by himself to the Victim or in satisfaction of amounts owed by the Victim were not shown, by evidence adduced, to have been made by the Accused at all.

41     The only evidence which the Accused was able to point to, in support of his submission, were the evidently self-serving statements he made at trial. He did not even make such assertions earlier in the statements he gave to the police.

42     This was the case for a series of payments listed in the Accused’s closing submissions, with the exception of two sets of payments made to the DBS Card and a UOB Cashplus Account, both maintained in the name of the Victim, amounting to S$3,500 (in relation to the DBS Card) and $950 (in relation to the UOB Cashplus Account).

43     In my view, the Accused’s claim that these payments support the existence of the Agreement is without merit when considered alongside the other evidence adduced.

44     The amounts which were withdrawn from the Victim’s accounts by the Accused far outstrip the sums which he was paying into the same accounts. Equally significantly, following the routing of the funds gives the impression that the payments by the Accused went towards repaying or facilitating unauthorised cash withdrawals made by the Accused from the Victim’s accounts.

45     To further elaborate, as mentioned earlier, the Accused sought, in trying to establish the existence of the Agreement, to place weight on two deposits amounting in aggregate to a sum of S$3,500 into the DBS Card account. These two deposits took place on 16 and 17 July 2015.

46     However, the DBS Card account was also an account from which the Accused was alleged to have made unauthorised withdrawals which are the subject matter of the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges. Pursuant to these Charges, the Accused is alleged to have, between 14 July 2015 and 6 August 2015, made unauthorised cash withdrawals from the DBS Card account amounting in total to S$14,620. This was around the same period when the deposit of S$3,500 made by the Accused into the DBS Card account was carried out.

47     A similar trend can be observed in relation to the deposit of S$950 into the Victim’s UOB Cashplus Account.

48     An aggregate sum of $950 was paid by the Accused into the UOB Cashplus Account between 16 July 2015 and 3 August 2015.

49     During that same period, on 15 and 16 July 2015, the Accused had made transfers totalling $5,200 _out_ of the UOB Cashplus Account into the Victim’s UOB Lady’s Card account. The Victim’s UOB Lady’s Card account was, in turn, an account from which the Accused made unauthorised _cash_ withdrawals, which took place both before and after 16 July 2015.

50     It bears noting that the Accused admitted to having withdrawn or transferred to his own bank account a sum of approximately $45,000 (excluding the amounts which were transferred to pay for the Victim’s credit cards) during the material period. The Accused was not able to satisfactorily explain why the Victim would have consented to or given authority for the withdrawal of such an amount.

51     The Accused’s assertion that the withdrawals forming the subject matter of the Charges were carried out pursuant to the Agreement is even more incredible when one considers that the sum of $45,000 mentioned earlier was withdrawn or transferred in the space of less than two months from 23 June 2015 to 16 August.

52     In the correspondence between the Victim and Accused, including exchanges adduced in evidence by the Accused himself, there are repeated references to the need to be careful with their finances.

53     The Victim gave evidence that whilst she did on occasion allow the Accused to use her credit cards to make purchases, she was present when these transactions took place[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8). It is also clear, from the Victim’s evidence, that she did not grant to the Accused any _general_ authority to use her funds, as contended for by the Accused.

#### Payments made between the Victim’s own accounts by the Accused.

54     The Accused also sought to argue that the existence of the Agreement is supported by the fact that he arranged payments between different accounts belonging to the Victim.[\[note: 9\]](#Ftn_9)

55     Apart from the Accused’s own bare assertions, there is no evidence that the Victim gave the Accused any general authority to make transactions using her Cards or bank accounts.

56     In any event, one key issue under consideration is whether, in carrying out the fund transfers referenced in the Charges, the Accused acted with the authority or consent of the Victim. Accordingly, the existence of transfers carried out by the Accused between the Victim’s accounts cannot be probative of the Victim’s consent.

#### The Victim did not make many transactions of her own.

57     The Accused argued that because the Victim did not make many transactions of her own, this supports the Accused’s submission that he was the one handling the Victim’s finances.

58     This submission is unconvincing. It appears from the evidence adduced that the Victim was careful with her money.

59     The Victim was also alive to the need to conserve funds for her school fees. At trial, the Victim stated that her POSB Account was used to save up funds for her “part-time university school fees”.[\[note: 10\]](#Ftn_10)

60     The lack of transactions carried out by the Victim seem to this court to show the Victim’s lack of means as well as a reluctance to spend, instead of showing the existence of the Agreement contended for by the Accused. I would add that since the Victim’s financial circumstances and reluctance to spend were communicated to the Accused by the Victim, this is also inconsistent with the Accused’s submission that he was acting under a belief that there was an Agreement between himself and the Victim permitting him to carry out transactions, _regardless of the amount involved_, on her behalf.

#### The romantic relationship between the Accused and the Victim

61     It is not disputed that at the time of the alleged offences, the Accused and the Victim were in a romantic relationship.

62     It is also not disputed that in the course of this relationship, the Accused delayed his return to Australia and stayed in Singapore with the Victim. The Victim also accepted that the Accused took care of her when she was ill, saw to her meals and accompanied her to doctors’ visits.

63     The foregoing, however, does not lead inexorably to the conclusion that the Victim must therefore have conferred on the Accused a general authority to have recourse to the Victim’s funds. It was still incumbent upon the Accused to demonstrate the existence of such an Agreement by adducing evidence, to which the existence of a romantic relationship could perhaps have lent further weight.

64     In the absence of such evidence, the ostensibly romantic relationship between Accused and Victim loses its significance insofar as the Charges are concerned.

### Evidence against the existence of an Agreement

65     Set against the Accused’s submissions, there is evidence which supports a finding that there was in fact no Agreement in existence between the Accused and the Victim and, further, that the Accused had no reason to believe there was.

#### The Accused’s statements to the police

66     At trial, the Prosecution adduced a total of three statements made by the Accused to the police.

67     These statements were recorded from the Accused on 18 March 2016, 8 December 2016 and 13 December 2016. The recorders of the Statements were, respectively:

> (a)     Ms Siti Faizah binte Abdullah (recorder of the 18 March 2016 statement); and

> (b)     ASP Ng Yong Da Justin (recorder of the 8 and 13 December 2016 statements).

68     Both of the aforementioned recorders gave evidence as witnesses for the Prosecution. Both confirmed, in essence, that the Accused had provided the information recorded in the statements and that he had given the three statements voluntarily.

69     The Accused did not challenge the admissibility of any of the three statements he gave to the police. The Accused did, at the time the statements were recorded in March and December 2016, inform the recorders Ms Siti Faizah and ASP Ng that he was undergoing psychiatric treatment. That being said, both recorders also gave evidence that notwithstanding this, the Accused did not mention that he was unwell and was prepared to go through with the statement recording. Both statement recorders also stated that the recording process would have been stopped had the Accused indicated he was unwell.[\[note: 11\]](#Ftn_11)

70     The Accused called no witness to adduce objective evidence of the nature of his psychiatric treatments or the condition for which he was being treated, despite being afforded numerous opportunities to do so. As such, I saw no reason to accord reduced weight to the statements given by the Accused to the police, either on account of any treatment the Accused was receiving or any medication he was taking, or on account of any particular condition from which the Accused alleged he was suffering, at the time the statements were recorded from him.

71     In all three of his statements, the Accused did not once mention the existence of any Agreement between himself and the Victim which the Accused now contends would exonerate him of the Charges. Instead, the Accused chose to _admit to wrongdoing_ in his statements given to the police on 18 March 2016 and 8 December 2016.

72     In his statement dated 18 March 2016, the Accused stated, _inter alia_, that he had taken the Victim’s credit cards “when she was sleeping” and, when asked how he had obtained the Victim’s PIN number, that “There were bank letters lying around. The PIN number was there on the bank letter.”

73     In his statement of 8 December 2016, the Accused stated, _inter alia_, that

> I wish to state that I am sorry misusing \[the Victim’s\] funds without her knowledge, I had done so because I wanted to use the money to take care of her and be a good boyfriend to her. I had used the money on our daily needs and I wanted to portray a good image to \[the Victim\]. That was the reason why I had made unauthorised fund withdrawal and transfer.

74     The Accused did not resile from these admissions in his 13 December 2016 statement to the police; to the contrary, that statement saw the Accused identifying specific transactions, recorded in bank statements shown to him, which he had made using the Victim’s banking facilities.

75     The admissions by the Accused in his police statements were not of a general nature but instead explicitly identified his wrongdoing.

76     It is simply incredible that the Accused would have made such statements to the police without mentioning the Agreement or alluding to its existence, but choose instead to admit wrongdoing, if the Agreement did exist or if the Accused believed it existed.

77     It bears highlighting that the statements in question were recorded over a period of time in March and December 2016. This was also some time after the Victim had first lodged a police report (in August 2015) about unauthorised transactions being made from her accounts. The Accused therefore had ample time to recall the existence of the Agreement before giving his statements to the police.

#### Payments made by the Accused’s parents to the Victim

78     I also note that from 21 March 2016 to 7 January 2019, multiple payments were made by the Accused’s mother to the Victim. These payments amounted, in aggregate, to a sum of S$11,165.

79     The Prosecution has characterised these payments as being restitutionary in nature, that is, these were sums intended to compensate the Victim for the financial loss she had suffered as a result of the Accused’s unauthorised acts. The Prosecution submits that the fact these restitutionary payments were made also suggested that the Accused knew he had engaged in wrongdoing in relation to the Victim’s financial resources.

80     The Accused did not agree with this characterisation of the payments made by his mother. He sought to portray the payments as having been made by his parents after the Victim demanded money from them from February 2016 onwards.

81     In his closing submissions, the Accused put forward two different reasons for his parents’ payments.

82     First, he claimed that his parents made the payments because they “appreciated the \[Victim\] for housing \[the Accused\].”[\[note: 12\]](#Ftn_12) Secondly, he claimed that his mother had paid the Victim out of sympathy.[^13]

83     These reasons are quite incredible. The Accused’s matter was first mentioned in court on 30 March 2017. If appreciation or sympathy had underpinned the Accused’s parents’ payments before then, it is difficult to see how these could reasonably have continued to motivate the Accused’s parents to continue making payments to the Victim after their son had been charged in court with wrongdoing in relation to the Victim’s financial resources, particularly if they had believed that the Accused was innocent of such wrongdoing, or why the Accused himself allowed his parents to continue paying the Victim, if he was of the view that the acts, for which he had been charged, had been authorised by the Victim.

84     Yet the Accused’s parents continued to make payments to the Victim after he was charged. Based on Exhibit P15, after the Accused was charged in court, his parents made a further 11 more payments to the Victim, of amounts ranging between $200 and $2,600.

85     Lest it be thought that his parents were the only parties who were amenable to making payments to the Victim, I should also add that the Accused himself evinced a willingness to make restitution to the Victim – In his statement to the police of 8 December 2016, Exhibit P17, the Accused stated, _inter alia_, that

> I wish to state that I am willing to make restitution to \[the Victim\]. However, I am only able to make the restitution by instalment.

#### The Victim’s evidence

86     The Victim herself was unequivocal in stating that there was no Agreement between herself and the Accused.

87     This was not only confirmed by the Victim during the trial,[\[note: 14\]](#Ftn_14) but also supported by the contents of the Victim’s police report of 17 August 2015 (Exhibit P14), in which she had reported that someone had made cash withdrawals and transfers from her accounts without her knowledge.

88     If the Agreement had existed between the Victim and the Accused, it is implausible that the Victim would not have first asked the Accused if the transactions had been made pursuant to the Agreement, as the Victim and the Accused were still in a romantic relationship at the time. Instead, she chose to report the transactions on the basis in a way that clearly showed she did not know who had made them and could not contemplate why they had been made.

89     It was submitted by the Accused that the Victim was not a helpful witness. In particular, he alleged that:

> (a)     the Victim was unable to recall many details of matters which took place during the period when the Charges were committed although she could recall not having consented to the Accused carrying out the particular transactions which were the subject matter of the Charges; and

> (b)     the Victim sought to “sidestep” the Accused’s questions in cross-examination by commenting on the questions instead of answering or seeking clarification on them.

90     I accept that the Victim did not directly answer some of the questions put to her by the Accused in cross-examination. However, it is not apparent that her responses to these questions should lead this court to conclude that she had been untruthful about the evidence which she did give, including her evidence as to the existence of the Agreement.

91     A significant proportion of the questions cited by the Accused in his closing submissions were essentially variations on a common theme, specifically, whether the Victim could recall specifically asking or allowing the Accused to make payments of her credit card bills[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15).

92     The Victim’s answer to a number of these questions was that she could not recall the information which the Accused sought to elicit from the Victim or that the Accused’s questions were too vague.

93     The cross-examination of the Victim was carried out by the Accused himself, as he was not represented by counsel at the time. In light of this, it is not surprising that the Victim would have been careful in how she responded to the Accused’s questions.

94     Further, the Accused has not adduced evidence to show that the Victim was withholding information which she could or should have provided in response to the Accused’s questioning. In the absence of such evidence, there is no basis for finding that the Victim was an untruthful witness who was selective in the facts she chose to present to court.

95     Having heard the Victim give testimony over a period of roughly two days, I would observe that the evidence given by the Victim was generally consistent, both internally as well as with the other evidence adduced, by the Prosecution as well as the Accused himself.

96     As such, having regard to the Victim’s evidence as a whole, I found no reason to disbelieve the Victim as a witness on the salient matters pertaining to the Charges. In particular, I do not see any basis for disbelieving the Victim’s assertion that there was no Agreement and that she did not give consent for the Accused to make the withdrawals or carry out the transactions which are the subject matter of the Charges.

### Conclusion as to existence of the Agreement and the Accused’s belief in its existence

97     I find that the Accused’s claims of an Agreement, pursuant to which he was allegedly conferred general authority by the Victim to make withdrawals or carry out transactions from the Victim’s account or using her credit card, regardless of amount, are not supported by evidence.

98     I further find that there was also no evidence which could give rise to reasonable doubt as to the existence of a _belief_, on the part of the Accused, that there was such an Agreement. In other words, the Accused did not actually believe that there was such an Agreement.

99     With the foregoing in mind, I set out below the grounds for my decision in relation to each category of Charges brought against the Accused.

## The Stolen Card Charges

100    The Accused was charged with misappropriating the ATM and credit cards listed in \[9\] above from the Victim.

### Removal of the Cards from the Victim’s possession

101    As mentioned earlier, the Victim testified that, during the period when the Accused resided with her, he had the opportunity of gaining access to the Victim’s mobile phone, laptops, house key and letter box key.[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16)

102    The Accused admitted at various points that he moved four of the five Stolen Cards out of the Victim’s possession:

> (a)     In his statement to the police dated 18 March 2016, the Accused stated, _inter alia_, as follows:

>> I was asked by IO Siti Faizah on whether I know what the purpose of my interview is today.

>> I roughly think I know.

>> I was asked by IO Siti Faizah on what was it that you know.

>> I knew that I had done something wrong which was using \[the Victim’s\] cards without her knowledge.

>> I was asked by IO Siti Faizah on what are the cards that I used.

>> I used \[the Victim’s\] DBS, Citibank and UOB credit cards.

> (b)     In his statement to the police dated 8 December 2016, the Accused admitted to withdrawing “money from Felicia’s credit card without her knowledge to pay for her medical bills” and that “With her credit card, I used it at the ATM to make withdrawal of $2000 to $3000 each time without her knowledge”. He also expressly stated that “I cannot remember what the credit cards were but remember that there were Citibank, UOB and DBS cards”.

> (c)     Under cross-examination by the DPP, the Accused expressly admitted that he removed the POSB Card, Citi Card, DBS Card and UOB Lady’s Card from the Victim’s possession.[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17)

103    To the above, I would add that the Accused also admitted to making withdrawals using the four Stolen Cards which he had appropriated from the Victim.[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18)

104    The Accused denied, however, that he removed the UOB Cashplus Card from the Victim’s possession.[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19)

105    The submission that the UOB Cashplus Card had been removed by the Accused from the Victim’s possession was premised on assertions by the Victim and the existence of unauthorised fund transfers made from the UOB Cashplus Account.

106    However, the unauthorised fund transfers, documented in statements for the UOB Cashplus Account (the account from which funds were transferred) and the Victim’s UOB Lady’s Card account (the account to which the funds were transferred),[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20) were carried out by way of online banking, which would not have required the Accused to have been in possession of the physical bank card.

107    The transactions involving outward fund movements recorded in the statement for the UOB Cashplus Account were annotated as “iBK” and the corresponding inward fund movements in the statement for the Victim’s UOB Lady’s Card were annotated as “PAYMT THRU E-BANK/HOMEB/CYBERB”. It was accepted by the Prosecution that these annotations show that the transactions in question were carried out using online banking facilities which did not require the Accused to be in possession of the UOB Cashplus Card to make the transactions in question.

108    Further, the Victim in her own testimony accepted that the “iBK” annotation could refer to an online banking transaction.[\[note: 21\]](#Ftn_21)

109    As such, even though unauthorised fund transfers (dealt with later in these Grounds) had been carried out by the Accused from the UOB Cashplus Account, it does not follow that the Accused was therefore at some point in possession of the Victim’s UOB Cashplus Card.

110    Accordingly, in relation to the 53rd Charge, being the Stolen Card Charge pertaining to the UOB Cashplus Card, I found that the Prosecution had not established beyond reasonable doubt that the Accused removed the UOB Cashplus Card from the Victim’s possession. The Accused was thus eventually acquitted on the 53rd Charge.

111    A submission was also made by the Accused, in his closing submissions[\[note: 22\]](#Ftn_22), that the Victim, contrary to her assertions, appeared to have used the UOB Lady’s Card on a number of occasions in July and August 2015, during the same period when it is alleged that the Accused had used this card to make unauthorised cash withdrawals.

112    In my view, even if transactions not attributable to the Accused were made on the UOB Lady’s Card in July and August 2015, this does not _per se_ establish that the Accused had not removed the UOB Lady’s Card from the possession of the Victim during this period.

113    The evidence adduced during the trial points inexorably towards the Accused having been in possession of the UOB Lady’s Card at the time when the unauthorised withdrawals linked to the UOB Lady’s Card were made.

114    As mentioned earlier, the Accused has admitted to removing, _inter alia_, the UOB Lady’s Card from the Victim’s possession.

115    Further, the Accused also admitted to making withdrawals, which I found not to have been authorised by the Victim, using the Stolen Cards (excluding the UOB Cashplus Card).[\[note: 23\]](#Ftn_23)

116    For the purposes of the Stolen Card Charge pertaining to the UOB Lady’s Card, what is key is that _at the point when the Accused took possession of the UOB Lady’s Card_, he did not have the Victim’s consent. In this case, there was no evidence of the Victim’s consent (general or specific as to occasion and time) to the Accused removing the Cards from her possession during the period encompassed by the Stolen Card Charges.

117    In any event, at trial, the Accused did not conduct his defence to the Stolen Card Charge relating to the UOB Lady’s Card on the basis that he had _never_ removed the UOB Lady’s Card from the Victim’s possession. To the contrary, the Accused’s position was that he had the consent or authority of the Victim to make the withdrawals in question. In the premises, his submission that the Victim may have used the UOB Lady’s Card in July and August 2015 do not aid his case.

### Lack of consent

118    According to the Accused, the Victim had given her consent for the Accused to access the Cards and to use them as part of the Agreement.

119    I have already found that there was no Agreement and also that there is insufficient evidence to show that the Accused believed there was. As such, any attempt by the Accused to rely on the existence (real or perceived) of an Agreement to show that the Victim consented to the removal of the Cards from her possession is without merit.

120    As mentioned at \[102\] above, the Accused admitted to removing the Victim’s credit cards from the Victim’s possession without her knowledge.

121    The Accused attempted to downplay the significance of the statements he gave to the police by drawing a distinction between lack of knowledge and lack of consent.

122    Specifically, he argued that whilst he had admitted to having carried out various acts (including but not limited to the taking of Stolen Cards from the Victim’s possession) without her knowledge, this was not the same as admitting that he had carried out those acts without her consent.[\[note: 24\]](#Ftn_24)

123    The Accused submitted that because of the Agreement, which vested in the Accused general authority to handle the Victim’s finances, the Victim was to be deemed to have consented to acts and financial transactions carried out on her behalf by the Accused even when she had no knowledge of the same.

124    With respect, the position taken by the Accused is not consistent with any reasonable reading of the statements he gave to the police.

125    The Accused made no attempt, in the statements he gave to the police, to explain that the Victim consented to his removal of the Cards from her possession even if she was not aware of the same. To the contrary, in the statement dated 18 March 2016,[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25) the Accused candidly stated that he knew that using the Victim’s Cards “without her knowledge” was tantamount to his having “done something wrong”.

126    Whilst the Accused tried to downplay the significance of his statements by asserting that he was suffering from a psychiatric treatment at the time of recording of his statements, as mentioned earlier,[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26) he adduced no evidence of his condition or the treatment he was receiving for the same to demonstrate why or how his statements to the police should be accorded reduced weight.

127    In relation to the UOB Lady’s Card, another submission made by the Accused in his closing submissions was that the Victim should have noticed that the UOB Lady’s Card was missing, because there were a number of transactions, recorded in the bank statements pertaining to this Card, in July and August 2015. Presumably, the intended effect of this submission was to cast doubt on the Victim’s assertion that she did not know about and hence had not consented to the use of the UOB Lady’s Card by the Accused.

128    With respect, it is not clear how the fact that transactions were made on the UOB Lady’s Card in July and August 2015 leads inexorably to the conclusion that the Victim “should have been on alert earlier that her card is missing”.[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27) The Accused did not lead evidence to demonstrate that because the Victim used the UOB’s Lady Card in July and August 2015, she should have been aware that the Accused had also made transactions using the same.

129    On the Victim’s part, it was her evidence that she had not given permission to the Accused _generally_ to take possession of or to use the Stolen Cards, notwithstanding his ability to gain access to them. Instead, the Victim gave evidence that she herself did not use some of the Stolen Cards.[\[note: 28\]](#Ftn_28)

130    The Victim accepted she had, on occasion, allowed the Accused to make transactions using her banking facilities. However, she maintained that she had specifically given her permission to the Accused to make these transactions using her cards and that the transactions were made in her presence.[\[note: 29\]](#Ftn_29)

131    In view of the foregoing, I am satisfied that the Accused had removed the Stolen Cards (apart from the UOB Cashplus Card) from the possession of the Victim without her consent.

### Dishonesty

132    It is provided in section 24 of the PC that a person (defined as “**A**”) does an act “dishonestly” if:

> (a)      _A_ does that act with the intention of causing wrongful gain to _A_ or another person, or wrongful loss to another person, regardless of whether such gain or loss is temporary or permanent; or

> (b)     that act done by _A_ is dishonest by the ordinary standards of reasonable and honest persons and _A_ knows that that act is dishonest by such standards.

133    The Prosecution submitted that the evidence adduced shows that the Accused possessed both an intention to cause wrongful gain to himself and to cause wrongful loss to Felicia.[\[note: 30\]](#Ftn_30) I agreed with this submission.

134    “Wrongful gain” and “wrongful loss” are defined in section 23 of the PC as follows:

> **“Wrongful gain” and “wrongful loss”**

> 23.—(1)    A “wrongful gain” is gain by unlawful means of property to which the person gaining it is not legally entitled or avoidance by unlawful means of a loss of property to which the person avoiding it is not legally entitled to avoid.

> \[15/2019\]

> (2)    A “wrongful loss” is loss or exposure of risk to a loss by unlawful means of property to which the person losing it or exposed to the risk of losing it is legally entitled.

> _Explanation_ 1.—A person is said to gain wrongfully when the person retains wrongfully, as well as when the person acquires wrongfully. A person is said to lose wrongfully when the person is wrongfully kept out of any property, as well as when the person is wrongfully deprived of property.

> _Explanation_ 2.—The word “gain” includes a gain by keeping what one has, as well as a gain by getting what one does not have.

> _Explanation_ 3.—The word “loss” includes a loss by not getting what one might get, as well as a loss by parting with what one has.

135    Insofar as the Stolen Card Charges (excluding the Charge pertaining to the UOB Cashplus Card) are concerned, the Victim suffered wrongful loss if and when, without her consent, the Accused removed the Stolen Cards (to which the Victim was legally entitled) from her possession, thereby keeping her out of, or causing her to be deprived of, the Stolen Cards. This loss was intentionally caused by the Accused, who was aware when he took possession of the Stolen Cards that he did not have the permission of the Victim to do so.

136    It is clear from section 24 of the PC that _permanent_ deprivation is not required for the Accused to be acting dishonestly. This principle was not seriously challenged by the Accused’s counsel.

137    Accordingly, I found that the Accused had acted dishonestly in removing the Stolen Cards (excluding the UOB Cashplus Card) from the Victim’s possession without her consent.

### Conclusion on Charges pertaining to the theft of the Victim’s bank and credit cards

138    By virtue of the foregoing, with the exception of the Charge pertaining to the theft of the UOB Cashplus Card, I found that the elements of the Stolen Card Charges were made out beyond reasonable doubt.

139    Accordingly, I found the Accused guilty of and convicted him on the 49th, 50th, 51st and 52nd Charges and recorded a discharge amounting to acquittal for the 53rd Charge.

## Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges

140    The Accused is alleged to have used some of the Victim’s Cards to make unauthorised cash withdrawals from ATM machines. Specifically, he faces:

> (a)     6 Charges pertaining to the Citi Card;

> (b)     10 Charges pertaining to the DBS Card;

> (c)     10 Charges pertaining to the UOB Lady’s Card; and

> (d)     1 Charge pertaining to the POSB Card (used to make a withdrawal from the Victim’s POSB Savings Account).

### Removal from Victim’s possession

141    The property which is the subject matter of the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges are the funds, belonging to the Victim, which were withdrawn using the Victim’s Cards.

142    The Accused admitted that he had made all the withdrawals mentioned in the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges. Specifically, in the course of recording his statement to the police dated 13 December 2016,[\[note: 31\]](#Ftn_31) the Accused was shown copies of bank statements pertaining to the Victim’s bank accounts and asked to identify transactions which he (as opposed to the Victim) had made. The Accused did so by drawing boxes around transactions which the Victim had made, and asserted in the statement that “These box out transactions were made by Felicia herself. As for the remaining transaction such as payment and withdrawal, it was all made by me.”

143    A review of the cash withdrawals identified by the Accused as having been made by himself reveals that these withdrawals corresponded to those encompassed by the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges.

144    Further, at trial, the Accused was again taken through the bank statements and asked to confirm that he had made each transaction encompassed by the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges. He duly admitted to having made the withdrawals in question.[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32)

### Lack of Consent

145    The Accused’s submissions on the elements of lack of consent and dishonesty in relation to the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges were essentially the same as those mentioned in relation to the Stolen Card Charges, that is, that there was an Agreement between the Accused and the Victim pursuant to which the Accused was permitted to carry out financial transactions, including to make cash withdrawals, on behalf of the Victim.

146    I have already found that there was no such Agreement. As such, this submission is without merit.

147    Instead, I prefer the evidence given by the Victim (whom I have found to be a generally reliable witness), who gave evidence that she did not consent to any of the withdrawals.[\[note: 33\]](#Ftn_33)

### Dishonesty

148    The Accused intended to and gave evidence that he used the withdrawn funds to pay for various goods and services in order to give the Victim the impression that he was financially supporting her and was therefore a “good boyfriend”[\[note: 34\]](#Ftn_34).

149    Even though the Victim benefited from some of these goods and services, this does not mean that the Accused was not acting dishonestly in making the unauthorised withdrawals.

150    The Accused made the withdrawals which are the subject of the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges without the Victim’s consent. As these were funds to which the Accused was not legally entitled but to which the Victim _was_ legally entitled, in making the said withdrawals, the Accused occasioned wrongful loss to the Victim and obtained a wrongful gain to himself, within the meaning of those terms as defined in section 23 of the PC. This follows from the finding earlier in these Grounds that there was no Agreement between the Victim and the Accused.

151    In turn, these withdrawals therefore were made dishonestly, within the meaning of that term as defined in section 24 of the PC, because they had been made by the Accused with the intention of occasioning wrongful loss to the Victim and to obtain a wrongful gain for himself.

152    I should add that the Accused, in his statements to the police, admitted that he knew he was wrong to have withdrawn funds from the Victim’s accounts without her knowledge. In particular, in his statement to the police of 8 December 2016, he stated, _inter alia_, that he was “sorry” for “misusing her funds without her knowledge.”

153    I was thus satisfied that the Accused acted “dishonestly” in making the unauthorised withdrawals for the purpose of the Charges under consideration.

### Conclusion on the Unauthorised Withdrawals Charges

154    By virtue of the foregoing, I found that all the elements of the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges were made out beyond reasonable doubt. Accordingly, I found the Accused guilty of and convicted him on these Charges.

## Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges

155    Apart from making unauthorised cash withdrawals, the Accused was alleged to have made unauthorised fund transfers from accounts maintained by the Victim, in contravention of section 3(1) of the CMA. Specifically, he was alleged to have made:

> (a)     1 unauthorised transfer using the DBS Card;

> (b)     11 unauthorised transfers using the Victim’s UOB Cashplus Account; and

> (c)     9 unauthorised transfers involving two of the Victim’s POSB savings accounts.

156    Of the 21 unauthorised transfers that are the subject matter of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges, 10 Charges (being those involving the DBS Card and the Victim’s POSB Savings accounts) involved transfers of sums into a bank account maintained in the name of the Accused.

157    The remaining 11 transfers involved sums transferred from the Victim’s UOB Cashplus Account for the purpose of making payments to an account linked to the Victim’s UOB Lady’s Card.

### Causing a computer to perform a function for the purpose of securing access to a program or data held in a computer

158    The Accused did not dispute that he carried out the transfers which form the subject matter of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges using the Victim’s online banking facilities or ATM banking facilities. He admitted this both in his statement to the police of 13 December 2016[\[note: 35\]](#Ftn_35) as well as under cross-examination by the Prosecution[^36], in each case identifying the specific transactions encompassed by the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges.

159    The bank statements adduced at trial also supported such a finding, with the available bank statements for the accounts from which funds were transferred reflecting the specific outward payments which were the subject matter of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges, and the available transaction records for the account to which transfers or payments were made, reflecting the inward movement of the same funds.

160    One of the witnesses called by the Prosecution at trial was Inspector Mohamed Shahudin bin Abu Bakar, a police officer who served at one point as the Investigating Officer for the matters which are the subject of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges.

161    Inspector Mohamed Shahudin gave evidence that he had been sent a letter from DBS Bank[\[note: 37\]](#Ftn_37) containing the transaction records for the Accused’s POSB savings account named in those of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges involving transfers from the Victim’s accounts to the Accused’s account.[^38] He further confirmed that each of the transactions, which is the subject matter of an Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charge involving transfers from the Victim’s accounts to the Accused’s account, can be found reflected in the Victim’s bank statements adduced in evidence and corresponds with a matching entry in the transaction records produced by DBS Bank for the Accused’s account.[^39]

162    I thus found beyond reasonable doubt that the Accused did carry out the transfers which are the subject matter of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges, and had in so doing necessarily caused a computer to perform a function for the purpose of securing access to a program held in a computer.

### Absence of authority

163    The parties agreed that in order to make out the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges, the Prosecution would have to show that the Accused had _actual knowledge_ that in making the transfers forming the subject matter of those Charges, he did not have the authority of the Victim to do so. The parties were in agreement that the existence of such actual knowledge can be inferred from the available evidence and does not turn solely on the Accused’s evidence as to the state of his mind at the time of the transfers.

164    Here, as with the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges, the Accused’s submission was that he was authorised, or at least believed he was authorised, pursuant to the Agreement, to make the transfers that are the subject of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges. He did not put forward any other basis upon which he could have been authorised by the Victim to make the transfers under consideration.

165    I have found earlier that there was no Agreement between the Accused and the Victim, and that the Accused did not actually believe in the existence of the Agreement at the material time.

166    In his statement to the police of 8 December 2016, the Accused expressly referred to his having made “unauthorised” fund transfers.[\[note: 40\]](#Ftn_40)

167    At trial, the Victim affirmed that she had never given the Accused any authority to the Accused to gain access to her online banking facilities or consented to him doing so.[\[note: 41\]](#Ftn_41)

168    The Victim gave evidence that she had not even been aware of the UOB Cashplus facility “until these fraudulent charges occurred”.[\[note: 42\]](#Ftn_42)

169    I saw no reason to doubt the Victim’s evidence on this point.

170    The Victim gave evidence that the transactions carried out using the Victim’s Accounts, which would have included the use of overdraft facilities in the form of the UOB Cashplus Account, exacted a professional toll on her, one that also had financial consequences.

171    When asked about the impact of the Accused’s actions on herself, the Victim answered as follows:

> Q    And, Ms. Lee, just one final question. Can you describe to the Court the impact these unauthorised transactions has had on you whether financially or emotionally?

> A    Financially, apart from all the credit cards and saving being cha---taken away from me, I had debts with my personal friends, that I had to sustained my own meals and his meal for the first few months when he was still staying with me. I have to struggle to pay off all the debts excluding the banks. And at work, I needed to build up my reputation again. And emotionally, I had to seek help with counsellor to go through all this trau---trauma.

> Q    You said at work, you needed to build up your reputation ag---again, can you explain to us why you needed to do that?

> A    Because a loan shark has made calls to my school on multiple occasions and my school leaders has to come about knowing it. I also have to declare my debts under---incurred under my name because of all these fraudulent charges. I have to go to MOE HQ for multiple interviews because of all these fraudulent charges. My bonuses and my lumpsum payment was held and delayed because of all this disciplinary issue that I have to face as a civil servant. And at work, as I’m in charge to oversee financial aspect, I have to take extra step to make sure that someone else know the decision I make at work just to make extra cautious for people to trust me again.

172    The Victim’s evidence in this regard was not challenged by the Accused.

173    Such evidence lent weight, in my view, to the Victim’s evidence that she did not confer authority on the Accused to have resort to the UOB Cashplus Account overdraft facility.

174    I found therefore that the evidence shows, beyond reasonable doubt, that the Accused knew he did not have the consent of the Victim to make the transfers which are the subject matter of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges.

### Conclusion on Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges

175    In light of the foregoing, I found that the Prosecution had shown each element of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges beyond reasonable doubt. I accordingly found the Accused guilty of and convicted him on all the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges.

## False Information Charge

### Procedural background: Amending the 54th Charge

176    At the commencement of the trial, the Accused faced one Charge under section 182 of the PC (the 54th Charge). This continued to be the case throughout the evidence taking stages of the trial and up to the point when the parties tendered their closing submissions in or around March 2021.

177    The 54th Charge, as originally framed, read as follows:

> You… are charged that you, on the 17th day of August 2015, at or about 10.20pm, at Kaki Bukit Neighbourhood Police Post located at Blk 526 Bedok North Street 3 #01-448, Singapore, did give one public servant, namely one Police Officer Tan Jun Seng Robin of the Singapore Police Force, information in Police Report No. G/20150817/2237 which you knew to be false, to wit, making a statement that you had no knowledge of how money was being transferred from one Lee Yen Pheng, Felicia’s POSB savings account into your POSB saving account, and that the transactions were done without your knowledge, intending thereby to cause such public servant to record the information in the said Report, which the said public servant would not have done if the true state of facts were known to him, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 182 of the Penal Code, Chapter 224.

178    At a hearing on 25 June 2021, I invited the Prosecution to consider its position in charging the Accused under section 182 of the PC as framed above, given the decision of the High Court in _PP v Chua Wen Hao and another appeal__[\[note: 43\]](#Ftn_43)_ (“**_Chua Wen Hao_**”).

179    In _Chua Wen Hao_, Sundaresh Menon CJ, giving the judgment of the General Division of the High Court, had that remarked section 182 of the PC

> …is not concerned with simply _any_ false statement made to a public servant, nor with simply _any_ effect caused by a false statement made to a public servant. Rather, it is concerned with the situation where a public servant _abuses, misuses or improperly withholds the use of his or her lawful powers_ as a result of a false statement made to him or her.[\[note: 44\]](#Ftn_44)

180    The High Court in _Chua Wen Hao_ then went on to clarify that there was a distinction between

> (a) powers that the police ought not to have exercised if all the true facts had been known to them; and (b) powers that the police were entitled or obliged to exercise but that they exercised in a manner which entailed or might have entailed greater expense and/or which was or might have been more extensive than what would otherwise have been the case…[\[note: 45\]](#Ftn_45)

181    It was highlighted to the Prosecution that, as originally framed, the act which the Accused had caused the police officer recording his statement of 17 August 2015 to undertake, which the police officer would purportedly not have done, was the act of recording the false information itself.

182    Following exchanges of submissions by the parties, the Prosecution eventually, at a hearing on 16 September 2021, made an application for the court to amend the 54th Charge to one brought under section 203 of the PC, in the exercise of the court’s power under section 128(1) of the Criminal Procedure Code (the “**CPC**”).

183    Section 203 of the PC provides as follows:

> **Giving false information respecting an offence committed**

> **203.** Whoever, knowing or having reason to believe that an offence has been committed, gives any information respecting that offence which he knows or believes to be false, shall be punished with imprisonment for a term which may extend to 2 years, or with fine, or with both.

184    In making its application for the court to amend the 54th Charge, the Prosecution accepted (and the Defence agreed) that, as originally framed under section 182 of the PC, the 54th Charge was deficient. In coming to this conclusion, the Prosecution’s submissions of 9 July 2022 referred to remarks in _Chua Wen Hao_ that section 182 of the PC is concerned with a situation where a public servant abuses, misuses or improperly withholds the use of his or her lawful powers as a result of false information provided by the Accused person who is charged under section 182.

185    In my view, this concession was properly made by the Prosecution, because it is not apparent how the recording of the putative false information by the police officer recording the Accused’s statement on 17 August 2015 would fall within the scope of section 182 of the PC as envisaged by the High Court in _Chua Wen Hao_. Specifically, it is not clear how the act of recording the statement would amount to a “situation where a public servant _abuses, misuses or improperly withholds the use of his or her lawful powers_ as a result of a false statement made to him or her”, insofar as the information was presented as being true by the person providing the same.

186    Counsel for the Accused resisted the Prosecution’s application to amend the 54th Charge to one under section 203 of the PC.

187    The Accused’s objection to the Prosecution’s application to amend the 54th Charge was premised upon the decision in _Goh Chin Soon v Public Prosecutor__[\[note: 46\]](#Ftn_46)_ (“**_Goh Chin Soon_**”). It was highlighted that in _Goh Chin Soon_, Hoo J had remarked that where a judge seeks to amend a charge _suo motu_ at the close of the Defence case, such amendments are to be constrained only to cases where the amended charge is made out on the existing evidence so as not to expose the Accused person to the risk of meeting a radically different or deficient case against him.[^47]

188    Applying this principle, counsel for the Accused argued that the evidence adduced at trial “did not point obviously to an offence. It is unclear that an offence had been committed, much less that the \[Accused\] knew or had reason to believe that an offence had been committed.”

189    In support of this submission, counsel for the Accused raised the following points[\[note: 48\]](#Ftn_48):

> (a)     Section 203 only applies to an accused who acts “knowing or having reason to believe that an offence has been committed”. As there was an Agreement between the Accused and the Victim, no offence had been committed in relation to withdrawals or transfers from the Victim’s accounts.

> (b)     The nature of the offence committed was unclear, because the information contained in the police report filed by the Accused on 17 August did not clearly relate to the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges involving transfers from the Victim’s POSB savings accounts to the Accused own account.

> (c)     There was no evidence pointing to the Accused’s knowledge or reason to believe that an offence relating to unauthorised access to the DBS online banking network had been committed at the time the Accused made his police report on 17 August 2015.

190    The Prosecution did not take serious issue with counsel for the Accused’s reliance on _Goh Chin Soon_, although I note that the Learned Judge had indicated that she was not in that case addressing the case where prosecution applies to amend the charge.[\[note: 49\]](#Ftn_49) Instead, the Prosecution’s response to the Accused’s objection was that the available evidence, at the point at which the amendment was being considered, was already sufficient to convict the Accused under the proposed amended Charge under section 203 of the PC.

191    After considering the parties’ submissions, I agreed with the Prosecution that the evidence adduced available to the court up to that point did in fact meet the requirements set out in _Goh Chin Soon_, that is, the offence reflected in the intended amended charge must be readily apparent from the evidence before the court and the prosecution must have discharged its evidential burden of proof on the intended amended charge given the state of the evidence and the stage of the trial.[\[note: 50\]](#Ftn_50)

192    It will be appreciated that the majority of the reasons put forward by the Accused in resisting the amendment application was premised on the Accused’s lack of knowledge or belief that the offences encompassed by the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges had been committed. I did not agree with these submissions by the Accused because evidence had already, by then, been adduced to demonstrate that the Accused was aware he acted without the Victim’s consent in, _inter alia_, making the transfers in question.

193    Further, insofar as the Accused sought to rely on the existence of the Agreement, for reasons which I have explained earlier and even based on the evidence adduced before the amendment to the 54th Charge was allowed, provisionally for the purposes of considering the amendment application, there was no Agreement between the Accused and the Victim, nor a belief on the part of the Accused that there was.

194    It should be added that the Accused did not submit that he would be prejudiced by the amendment of the 54th Charge. In any event, I note that the factual basis that underlies the amended charge under section 203 of the PC is essentially the same as that for the original charge under section 182 of the PC and that the Prosecution had confirmed, in making the amendment application, that it would not seek to adduce additional evidence if the 54th Charge was amended.

195    In the premises, pursuant to section 128(1) of the CPC, I directed at the hearing on 16 September 2021 that the 54th Charge be amended in terms proposed by the Prosecution, as set out in \[18\] above.

196    Thereafter, in accordance with section 128(2) of the CPC, the amended charge was read and explained to the Accused. The Accused then informed the court that he would be pleading not guilty to the amended 54th Charge and that he would be giving further evidence in respect of the amended charge.

197    As the Accused declared that he was not ready to proceed to give evidence in relation to the amended 54th Charge on 16 September 2021, the hearing was adjourned and a further hearing eventually took place on 12 November 2021 to record the Accused’s evidence in relation to the amended 54th Charge.

### Decision on conviction for the amended 54th Charge

198    Following the amendment of the 54th Charge, the Accused faced the False Information Charge set out in \[18\] of these Grounds. The False Information Charge alleges that the Accused, having reason to believe that an offence under section 3(1) of the CMA had been committed, gave false information respecting that offence to the police by stating, in a police report dated 17 August 2015, that he had no idea how money had been transferred from the Victim’s two POSB savings accounts into his own bank account.

#### Background to the False Information Charge

199    By way of background, on 17 August 2015, the Victim made a police report (Exhibit P14) alleging, _inter alia_, that a sum of “about $8,000” had been transferred from her two POSB savings accounts into a POSB account maintained in the name of the Accused. The Victim further stated in her police report in P14 that this sum of “about $8,000” was subsequently transferred out of the Accused’s POSB account into an “unknown London Bank account”.

200    Thereafter, on the same date, the Accused also made a police report (Exhibit P22). P22 records that the Accused referred to the transfer of $8,000 described in P14 and then made the following statement to the Recording Officer:

> I wish to further state that I have no idea how the money was being transferred from my girfriend’s \[_sic_\] POSB savings account into my POSB savings account.

> (the “**Material Statement**”)

201    Immediately following the Material Statement, the Accused added, in his police report in P22, that

> The transactions were done without my knowledge. I have no suspect.

202    It is alleged that the Material Statement was false, and that the Accused knew it to be false, because it related to the Accused’s transfer of funds from the Victim’s account to his own account. It is further alleged that the Material Statement was made in respect of offences which the Accused had reason to believe at the time had been committed, the offences being those committed by the Accused and which form the subject matter of the 40th to 48th Charges (some of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges).

#### The Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges have been made out

203    It is an essential element of the offence under section 203 of the PC that another offence has been committed. In this case, the other offence would be the offences encompassed by the 40th to 48th Charges.

204    I have already found that the 40th to 48th Charges are made out against the Accused.

#### The Material Statement contained false information

205    In light of the evidence adduced at trial, the Accused’s assertion in the Material Statement that he did not know how money had been transferred from the Victim’s account into his account was clearly false.

206    The Accused admitted that from 1 August 2015 to 16 August 2015, he transferred various amounts from the Victim’s POSB savings accounts into his own POB savings account.[\[note: 51\]](#Ftn_51) The aggregate sum which the Accused admitted to transferring was $8,208. These transfers by the Accused were made shortly before the police report in P14 was filed; indeed, the final transfer was made on 16 August 2015, only one day before the police report in P14 was made on 17 August 2015. This was confirmed by the Accused under cross-examination by the Prosecution.[^52]

207    The Accused also gave evidence that when the Victim was making her police report on 17 August 2015, he was present and had heard the contents of the Victim’s police report.[\[note: 53\]](#Ftn_53)

208    Further, the Accused claimed that he was “shocked” as the Victim made her police report, because he could not believe the Victim was telling the police that she had not been aware that her funds had been transferred from the Victim’s account to the Accused’s account. [\[note: 54\]](#Ftn_54) Implicit, in this assertion, is an admission by the Accused that he knew which fund transfers were the subject of the Victim’s police report in P14.

209    In addition, at the hearing on 12 November 2021 to take the Accused’s further evidence in relation to the False Information Charge, the Accused expressly acknowledged under cross-examination that he did know, _at the time he was making the police report in P22_, how the Victim’s monies had come to be transferred from her bank account into the Accused’s bank account.[\[note: 55\]](#Ftn_55)

210    Given that the Accused knew full well which transfers were being referred to by the Victim, the Accused would have been aware as well that he was the person who had made the transfers referred to in the Victim’s police report P14.

211    In light of this, it follows that the information given by the Accused to the police, as recorded in P22, that he had “no idea” how the money was being transferred, was false. Put differently, the Material Statement contained an assertion that he _lacked knowledge_ about the transfers mentioned in the Victim’s report in P14. This was false, because he had full knowledge of those transfers, having been the person who had made them.

#### The Accused knew that: (1) an offence had been committed and (2) the information he gave respecting that offence was false

212    It was not disputed that, in order to make out the False Information Charge against the Accused, the Prosecution had to show that in giving the false information contained in the Material Statement:

> (a)     The Accused knew or had reason to believe that an offence had been committed.

> (b)     The Accused knew or believed that the information he was giving respecting that offence was false.[\[note: 56\]](#Ftn_56)

##### (1)   The Accused knew or had reason to believe that an offence had been committed

213    The Accused submitted that he did not know or believe, when making the Material Statement, that an offence had been committed, because the purported Agreement between the Accused and the Victim conferred upon the Accused the authority to carry out the transfers which were referred to in the Victim’s police report of 17 August 2015[\[note: 57\]](#Ftn_57) and in respect of which the Accused was providing information to the police, in his own police report.

214    As mentioned earlier, the Accused knew, when he made the Material Statement, what transfers were being referred to by the Victim in her police report in Exhibit P14. He also knew, when making the police report containing the Material Statement, how moneys had come to be transferred from the Victim’s account to his account.[\[note: 58\]](#Ftn_58)

215    Since it is clear that the Accused knew, on 17 August 2015, which transfers were being referred to by the Victim in her police report of that date and consequently in the Accused’s police report of the same date (containing the Material Statement), the Accused’s knowledge as to whether an offence had been committed, when he was making his police report of 17 August 2015, turns on whether the Accused believed in the existence of such an Agreement.

216    I have already found that this purported Agreement between the Accused and the Victim did not exist and that the Accused at all material times did not believe that such an Agreement was in place.

217    It follows that on 17 August 2015, the Accused knew that he did not have the authority make the transfers to his own bank account, which were the subject of the Victim’s police report in P14. He therefore clearly had reason to believe, when making the Material Statement, that one or more than one offence had been committed in the making of the transfers.

218    If there was an Agreement between the Accused and the Victim, it is incredible that the Accused did not assert the existence of the same in making his statement on 17 August 2015.

219    In giving evidence pertaining to the False Information Charge, the Accused claimed to have been shocked to hear the Victim inform the police officer on 17 August 2015 that she had not been aware of the transfers made from her bank account. I reproduce the relevant passage recorded during examination-in-chief:

> Q    After Ms. Lee made the police report, what happened?

> A    Um, after Ms. Lee made the police report, um, the police officer actually, um, ask me that since Ms. Lee actually made a police report against me, um, would I have anything, um, to say?

> Q    What did you respond to the police officer?
