> A    Um, at that point of time I was actually, um, very, uh, shocked, because, um, when I was, um, listening to Ms. Lee making her police report, **I actually, um, did not believed that, um, she was, um, saying things like, um, she wasn’t aware of, um, her funds was transferred from her account to my account, because, um, we had a financial, um, arrangement**, um, between myself and Ms. Lee, so I was actually shocked and, um, and, um, I was actually shocked and I really, um, my mind was wasn’t, um, in the right frame of mind.

> (Emphasis added)

220    If the passage above truly reflected the Accused’s state of mind upon hearing the Victim’s words to the police officer on 17 August, this would mean that the Agreement was at the forefront of his thoughts that evening. It is inconceivable that under these circumstances, the Accused chose instead to knowingly give false information to the police by asserting his ignorance of the transfers, instead of putting forward a simple explanation that there was an Agreement in place.

221    I agree, therefore, with Prosecution that the Accused’s actions on 17 August 2015 run counter to the existence of the Agreement and further demonstrate that the Agreement was an afterthought by the Accused.

222    There is thus no merit in the Accused’s submission that he did not have any reason to believe that an offence had been committed.

223    The Accused sought, in his closing submissions of 17 December 2021 pertaining to the False Information Charge, to play up the lack of any opportunity for him to explain the details of the transfers to the Victim.

224    He claimed, in those submissions, that he had been focused on assuaging the Victim when he made the police report and that he had been prevented from explaining the transfers to the Victim because her colleague was present and insisted that the Victim make a police report.

225    With respect, I do not see how these circumstances[\[note: 59\]](#Ftn_59) prevented the Accused from raising the existence of the Agreement with either the police or the Victim on 17 August, or why he would have thought making the Material Statement, as opposed to raising the Agreement with the Victim, was the preferable course of action. These assertions are contrived and unbelievable.

226    I would add that the Accused was given an opportunity to read the police report after it had been typed out by the Recording Officer and make corrections before signing it. It is the unchallenged evidence of the Recording Officer that the Accused did not at any time inform him that he disagreed with anything recorded in P22.[\[note: 60\]](#Ftn_60)

##### (2)   The Accused knew that that the information he gave respecting the 40th to 48th Charges was false

227    I have already found earlier that Accused knew the Material Statement contained false information.

228    At various points in his testimony relating to the Material Statement, the Accused tried to make the point that that police statement had been made in stressful circumstances or that “little weightage should be relied on this police report…”.[\[note: 61\]](#Ftn_61)

229    To be clear, in referring to “stressful circumstances”, the Accused was not alleging any act or omission on the part of the Recording Officer or any other police officer that would have rendered the statement involuntary. Instead, what made the circumstances stressful was supposedly the fact that if for some reason the Victim no longer wished to allow the Accused to continue living with her, the Accused would not know where to go.[\[note: 62\]](#Ftn_62)

230    In his closing submissions, the Accused also argued that the situation was stressful for him because the Victim was present with one of her colleagues when he made the police report on 17 August 2015.

231    With respect, these facts raised by the Accused, even if true, can have no bearing on the question of conviction in relation to the False Information Charge, because they do not detract from the fact that the Accused knew he was, in making his police report on 17 August 2015, providing information to the police which was false.

232    In his written closing submissions of 17 December 2021, the Defence sought to argue, _inter alia_, that the False Information Charge was not made out because the Accused did not give information to police on the alleged offence.

233    To elaborate, it was submitted that P22 makes no reference to the False Information Charge “nor any offence of unauthorised access under section 3(1) of the \[CMA\].” Instead, it was submitted that the information which the Accused provided was “about the transfer, as opposed to accessing \[the Victim’s\] DBS iBanking network without authority.”

234    With respect, in my view this argument takes too narrow a view of the offence encompassed by the 40th to 48th Charges and what it means to give information “in respect of” those offences for the purpose of the False Information Charge.

235    In this case, the Accused was aware that he had made the transfers referred to by the Victim in her police report without the Victim’s knowledge or consent. He therefore had reason to believe that an offence had been committed in the carrying out of those transfers, even I accept if he may not have been aware as to which specific statutory provisions had been contravened.

236    The Accused knew that he was making a police report to respond to the Victim’s own police report regarding the transfers. Accordingly, the Material Statement was made by the Accused with reference to the transfers, which formed the factual bases for the offences encompassed by the 40th to 48th Charges. The Material Statement therefore in my view did contain false information “respecting” those offences for the purposes of section 203 of the PC.

237    In this regard, it would seem too narrow an interpretation of section 203 of the PC to hold that an accused person must be in a position to identify the specific offence constituted by a particular set of facts, before information which he volunteers in relation to that set of facts can form the basis for a conviction under section 203.

#### Conclusion on the False Information Charge

238    By virtue of the foregoing, I found that the Prosecution had proved every element of the False Information Charge beyond reasonable doubt. Accordingly, the Accused was found guilty of and convicted on the same.

## Conclusion: Conviction

239    In summary, I found the Accused guilty of all the Charges except for the 53rd Charge and convicted him accordingly on the remaining 53 Charges. For the 53rd Charge, I recorded a discharge amounting to acquittal.

240    In the remainder of these Grounds, I set out the reasons for the sentences which I imposed on the Accused, for the Charges on which he was convicted.

## Sentencing

241    There is no charge to be taken into consideration for the purposes of this sentencing.

242    After considering the parties’ submissions on sentence, I sentenced the Accused as set out in the sentencing table annexed to these Grounds.

## Sentences for individual charges

243    I first set out my reasons for imposing the sentence pertaining to each of the 53 Charges on which I have convicted the Accused, in accordance with the approach laid down by the High Court in _Mohamed Shouffee bin Adam v PP__[\[note: 63\]](#Ftn_63)_ (“**_Mohamed Shouffee bin Adam_**”).

### Theft Charges under section 379 of the Penal Code

244    The Accused was convicted on a total of 31 Charges brought under section 379 of the PC.

245    The prescribed punishments which may be imposed on the Accused for these offences are

> …imprisonment for a term which may extend to 3 years, or with fine, or with both.

246    These Charges can be further subdivided into the following two sub-categories:

> (a)     27 Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges; and

> (b)     4 Stolen Card Charges (the Accused having been acquitted of one of the Stolen Card Charges).

#### Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges

247    All the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges share a number of similar features. In essence, the Accused made cash withdrawals using credit or ATM cards he had separately stolen from the Victim.

248    The sums involved varied, ranging from $210 to $3,000.

249    In respect of each Unauthorised Withdrawal Charge, both the Prosecution and the Defence made submissions on the appropriate sentence primarily by reference to the sum stolen, with a sentence proposed for a specified range of sums.

250    The specific ranges proposed by the Prosecution and Defence are set out in the following table:

<table align="left" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="Judg-2-tblr" frame="all" pgwide="1"><colgroup><col width="50%"><col width="50%"></colgroup><tbody><tr><td align="left" class="br" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b><u>Prosecution’s position (per Charge)</u></b></p></td><td align="left" class="b" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="center" class="Table-Para-1"><b><u>Defence Counsel’s position (per Charge)</u></b></p></td></tr><tr><td align="left" class="r" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Less than $500: 1 to 2 weeks imprisonment</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">$500: 1 month’s imprisonment</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">$700 to $1,500: 2 months’ imprisonment</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">$2,000 to $3,000: 3 months’ imprisonment</p></td><td align="left" class="" rowspan="1" valign="top"><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Up to $1,000: 2 weeks’ imprisonment</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Above $1,000 and below $2,500: 1 month’s imprisonment</p><p align="justify" class="Table-Para-1">Between $2,500 and $3,000: 2 months’ imprisonment</p></td></tr></tbody></table>

  
  

251    Whilst the Prosecution and the Defence adopted different sentencing ranges, there is a degree of overlap in the sentences submitted for by both sides.

252    In considering the appropriate sentence for the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges, I agreed with the Prosecution that there are aggravating factors to be taken into account.

253    First, the Accused abused the trust reposed in him by the Victim in committing the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges.

254    The degree of trust reposed by the Victim in the Accused must have been high, because not only was she in a romantic relationship with the Accused at the material time, she allowed the Accused to reside with her. The Accused was afforded the opportunity to gain access to the Stolen Cards and information necessary to use them, because he was allowed by the Victim to move in with her.

255    The Accused’s abuse of the trust reposed in him by the Victim is aggravated by his lack of remorse at trial for his actions.

256    Second, I also agree it is significant that the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges comprised a series of repeated wrongful actions which took place over a period of time. Specifically, the Accused made 27 unauthorised cash withdrawals over a period of almost two months. The enhanced criminality demonstrated by these repeated instances of theft is an aggravating factor that should weigh significantly in deciding on the appropriate sentence.

257    Third, even though the largest amount pilfered by the Accused under the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges was $3,000, because these withdrawals were repeated on numerous occasions, a total of $36,760 was stolen from the Victim. The loss of this amount had an impact beyond merely depriving the Victim of the funds in question (See \[170\] to \[171\] of these Grounds above).

258    As far as mitigating factors are concerned, I agreed with the Prosecution’s submission that there was not any factor present which would merit a significant discount on the sentence to the imposed in this case. I will go through some of those that were raised by the Accused’s counsel.

259    First, it was submitted that the Accused committed the offences “as a result of misplaced love and affection for Ms Lee”. It was highlighted that he had spent at least part of the monies, which he withdrew without the Victim’s consent, on the Victim herself.

260    With respect, this is not in my view a mitigating factor in this case.

261    The substance of the Accused’s submission in this regard is that the sentence imposed on him should be reduced because he used the Victim’s own financial resources on the Victim.

262    These were resources that belonged to the Victim and which she was thus entirely entitled to utilise in any manner she may have wished. Given that the Accused’s actions took advantage of the Victim’s resources without the Victim’s consent or knowledge, in order to burnish his own image in the mind of the Victim, and in doing so caused the Victim to suffer adverse financial and professional consequences, I am hard pressed to see why any mitigatory weight ought to be accorded as submitted for by the Accused.

263    Separately, it was also submitted on behalf of the Accused that he had made payments to the Victim even as he withdrew money from the Victim’s accounts.[\[note: 64\]](#Ftn_64)

264    In my view, this argument can only carry limited mitigatory weight. No evidence was led to show that these payments, which in aggregate also amount to significantly less than the sum which was withdrawn by the Accused in the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges, emanated from the Accused.

265    In this regard, a perusal of the payments listed in paragraphs 23 and 24 of the Defence Sentencing Submissions dated 23 February 2022 reveals that the payments relied upon in support of this particular submission were made between 24 June 2015 and 3 August 2015. This was the same period when the Accused has been found to have made unauthorised cash withdrawals from the Victim’s accounts (the earliest withdrawal forming the subject matter of the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges having been made on 23 June 2015 [\[note: 65\]](#Ftn_65) and the last having been made on 7 August 2015[^66]).

266    The sentences submitted by the Prosecution were in line with the precedents they tendered.

267    In _PP v Hairul Faizal bin Mohamad Isa__[\[note: 67\]](#Ftn_67)_ (“**_Hairul Faizal_**”), the offender stole his brother’s ATM card to make unauthorised cash withdrawals. For theft of $1,000, the accused in that case was sentenced to two months’ imprisonment.

268    The _Hairul Faizal_ decision, whilst unreported, seems to present a reasonably direct comparable to the facts of the case before this court.

269    I am of the view that the sentences proposed by the Prosecution here for the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges are reasonable and appropriate, when one considers that the longest proposed sentence of three months’ imprisonment for theft charges involving sums of between $2,000 to $3,000 is comparable to (and arguably more generous than) the two months’ imprisonment meted out in the _Hairul Faizal_ case for theft (also using an ATM card) of amounts of $800 and $1,000.

270    In contrast, I find the sentences proposed by the Defence for the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges to be slightly low.

271    The case of _PP v Chan Puan Seng__[\[note: 68\]](#Ftn_68)_ (“**_Chan Puan Seng_**”) was one of the cases relied upon by the Accused’s counsel in support of her proposed tariffs for the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges. In that case, the accused person had also made unauthorised withdrawals using the ATM card of the victim, with whom he was in a romantic relationship. He was sentenced to two weeks’ imprisonment on each charge, _inter alia_, of twelve proceeded charges of theft under section 379 PC.

272    Whilst the facts of _Chan Puan Seng_ bear a superficial resemblance to those before me, it is clear that the Learned District Judge’s (“**DJ**”) decision in that case was influenced by factors which are absent from the case before this court.

273    At \[100\] of her Grounds of Decision, the DJ noted that

> Prior to \[the accused\] losing his employment, he had been very generous towards her and spent monies on her freely without the thought of asking her for repayment.

274    Specific examples of the accused’s generosity were also noted by the DJ in \[55\] of her Grounds of decision.

275    The above observations by the DJ accounted for the sentences she imposed on the accused, which she expressly said were “on the lower end of the usual range of sentences handed out for offences of this nature”.[\[note: 69\]](#Ftn_69)

276    The Accused in the present case bears no comparison to the one in _Chan Puan Seng_. Whilst I accept that he did take care of the Victim on occasion, there is simply no evidence that he bore anywhere near as much of the financial responsibilities which the accused in _Chan Puan Seng_ had borne. There is no evidence that he paid rental to the Victim for staying at her residence. Further, whilst there is some evidence that he paid for some of the Victim’s expenditure, a substantial amount came from the funds which he obtained as a result of the unauthorised withdrawals from the Victim’s account.

277    I am thus of the view that _Chan Puan Seng_ does not support the Accused’s submission that lower tariffs than those proposed by the Prosecution should be applied for the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges.

278    As for the other two cases cited by the counsel for the Accused, being _PP v Seet Choo Meng__[\[note: 70\]](#Ftn_70)_ and _PP v Teo Kai Lin[^71]_, the sentences of one month’s imprisonment for theft involving $1,000 are actually in line with Prosecution’s submissions, particularly when one considers that in those decisions the accused persons pleaded guilty to the charges in question, having regard as well to the existence of the aggravating factors I have highlighted earlier.

279    For offences involving between $2,000 to $3,000, the Prosecution’s submission of three months’ imprisonment is broadly consistent with the precedents tendered by the parties. In particular, I would highlight that the Prosecution’s submission is not inconsistent with the decision in _PP v R Balasubramaniam__[\[note: 72\]](#Ftn_72)_ (“**_R Balasubramaniam_**”), which was also an authority put forward by counsel for the Accused. Even though in _R Balasubramaniam_ sentences of two months’ imprisonment were imposed for some amounts of $3,000 and above, it is to be noted that there were significant mitigating factors present in that case which are absent here, the most significant being the fact that the accused in _R Balasubramaniam_ pleaded guilty and “clearly tried to make amends which was indicative of repentance”.[^73]

280    Having regard to the foregoing, for the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges, I accepted the tariffs put forward by the Prosecution as a preferable starting point, as compared to those put forward by the Accused.

281    That being said, I was of the view that some adjustment to the Prosecution’s tariffs were necessary, for offences with values ranging between $500 to $1,500. This was because the Prosecution’s proposed tariffs pegged the sentence for offences involving a value of exactly $500 at one month’s imprisonment, but then proposed an increase to two months for a large range of offences from $700 to $1,500. Given that the sums stolen were being used as a meaningful proxy for the degree of criminality involved in each Unauthorised Withdrawal Charge, there seemed to be no principled basis for enforcing a tariff with the uneven distribution proposed by Prosecution.

282    In view of this, for the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges, I applied the following tariffs in sentencing, with a slightly more linear progression of sentences for increasing amounts:

> (a)     For offences involving up to $500: one to two weeks’ imprisonment;

> (b)     For offences involving between $700 (there being no Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges involving between $501 to $699) to $1,000: one month’s imprisonment;

> (c)     For offences involving between $1,001 to $1,500: six weeks’ imprisonment; and

> (d)     For offences involving between $2,000 (there being no Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges involving between $1,501 to $1,999) to $3,000: three month’s imprisonment.

#### Stolen Card Charges (excluding 53rd Charge)

283    For each Charge relating to the Stolen Cards, the Prosecution submitted that a sentence of one month’s imprisonment would be appropriate.

284    The basis for this submission appears to be the sentences meted out in _Hairul Faizal_ (two months’ imprisonment for a charge pursuant to section 380 of the PC) and _PP v Biak Kim Sung__[\[note: 74\]](#Ftn_74)_ (“**_Biak Kim Sung_**”; three months’ imprisonment for a charge under section 381 of the PC).

285    On the part of the Accused, his counsel submitted that the appropriate sentence would be three weeks’ imprisonment for each of the Charges relating to the Stolen Cards.

286    This was based on the decision in _PP v Mihaly Magashazie__[\[note: 75\]](#Ftn_75)_ (“**_Mihaly Magashazie_**”), in which the accused was sentenced to a month’s imprisonment for each charge, under section 379 of the PC, of stealing credit cards from hotels in Singapore by prying open lockers in the male changing room and gym room of the hotels in question. The Accused’s counsel argues that the sentence in this case ought to be lower than that imposed in _Mihaly Magashazie_ because there were more aggravating factors in that case, and so proposed a sentence of three weeks’ imprisonment each for the Charges relating to the Stolen Cards.

287    With respect, whilst I agreed that _Mihaly Magashazie_ serves as a useful precedent as it also involved the theft of credit cards, I did not agree with counsel for the Accused that the sentence for the Accused in this case ought to be lower than one month. Insofar as the Accused here did not have to resort to forced entry in order to gain access to the Stolen Cards, this was only because the Accused abused the trust reposed by the Victim in him to steal the Stolen Cards. I do not see how such circumstances lend themselves to a lower sentence than that imposed in _Mihaly Magashazie_, and accordingly sentenced the Accused to one month’s imprisonment for each of the Charges relating to the Stolen Cards.

### Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges

288    The Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges can be broken down into two categories as follows:

> (a)     10 Charges involving unauthorised transfers of funds from the Victim’s accounts to the Accused’s own account; and

> (b)     11 Charges involving unauthorised transfers of funds from the Victim’s accounts to the Victim’s credit card account.

289    The applicable punishment provision in section 3(1) of the CMA provides that upon conviction, the Accused, as a first offender,

> …shall be liable on conviction to a fine not exceeding $5,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 2 years or to both…

290    The initial approach of both Prosecution and Defence, in relation to the sentences to be imposed for the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges, was that they should be calibrated by reference to the amounts that were transferred in each Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charge, and that similar tariffs to those applicable to the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges ought to be applied.

291    At the hearing on 25 February 2022, parties were asked to furnish further submissions on the issue of whether the sentencing approach for the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges ought to be differentiated, based on whether the unauthorised transfer in question was to the Victim’s credit card account or to the Accused’s own account. In particular, this court was concerned by the Prosecution’s characterisation of transfers from the Victim’s bank account to the Victim’s credit card account as a “loss” suffered by the Victim.

292    Further submissions were duly tendered by the Prosecution and the Accused’s counsel, and, in summary:

> (a)     The Prosecution still proposed to use the same sentencing tariffs for Charges involving both transfers to the Victim’s account and to the Accused’s account, although it conceded that transfers between the Victim’s accounts should not be considered a financial loss to the Victim. The Prosecution submitted, however, that this distinction need not affect consideration of the sentences for individual Charges, but instead could be considered when the overall loss suffered by the Victim, and hence the global sentence to be imposed on the Accused, came to be considered.

> (b)     In contrast, the Accused’s counsel took the view that in principle the sentences for Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges involving transfers between the Victim’s accounts should be lower than those for transfers to the Accused’s account, but that in practice, given the already low sentences proposed by the Accused for the majority of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges, only one of the previously proposed sentences (for the 28th Charge (MAC-903049-2017) involving a transfer of $5,000 between the Victim’s accounts would be affected.

293    Based on the foregoing, it will be apparent that whilst the positions taken by the Prosecution and the Defence were different in principle, there was little to distinguish between them in operation, save in relation to the 28th Charge, for which counsel for the Accused sought a sentence of two months’ imprisonment and the Prosecution sought a sentence of five months’ imprisonment.

294    Insofar as the tariffs to be imposed for Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges were concerned, both the Prosecution and Defence agreed that reference could be taken from the precedents relied upon by each party for the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges.

295    I agreed with parties that this would be a sound approach to take.

296    Whilst offences under section 3 of the CMA may not in every case involve a financial element, in the present instance, all of the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges of which the Accused has been convicted invariably did.

297    As I have already made findings earlier on the appropriate sentencing tariffs to be applied to the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges, and in line with the principle outlined above, for all the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges other than the 28th Charge, I applied the same tariffs decided upon for the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges to the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges.

298    The sentence for the 28th Charge was separately considered. This was because the sum involved in this Charge, being $5,000, was significantly larger than the largest sum involved in the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges, which was $3,000.

299    The Prosecution submitted for a sentence of five months’ imprisonment for the 28th Charge. The basis for this particular submission is not expressly stated in the submissions filed by the Prosecution, but it appears that Prosecution based this in part on the global sentences meted out in the _Hairul Faizal_ and _Biak Kim Sung_ cases, both of which involved aggregate sums stolen in the region of $5,000. In both _Hairul Faizal_ and _Biak Kim Sung_, the global sentence imposed was four months’ imprisonment.

300    In contrast to the Prosecution’s position, the sentence submitted by counsel for the Accused for the 28th Charge was two months’ imprisonment.

301    In support of this proposed sentence, counsel for the Accused cited the decision in _PP v Cheng Jun__[\[note: 76\]](#Ftn_76)_ (“**_Cheng Jun_**”).

302    In _Cheng Jun_, the accused pleaded guilty to 14 charges under the section 3(1) of the CMA for transferring funds, without authorisation, from the account of the company for which he worked, to his own bank accounts.

303    In explaining his decision on sentence in _Cheng Jun_, the Learned District Judge commented at \[24\] of his Grounds of Decision that he had considered, _inter alia_, that

> Based on the sentencing precedents for cases involving unauthorized fund transfers, the general ranges of imprisonment were in the region of 2 to 3 months for individual values of up to $5,000, 6 to 12 months for overall values of between $50,000 to $100,000 and more than 12 months for values exceeding $100,000. Admittedly, this is a rough and ready gauge based only on the monetary value of the amounts stolen and is only a starting point.

304    Counsel for the Accused in the case under consideration submitted that the comments above supported their submission that the sentence for the 28th Charge should be two months’ imprisonment.

305    I did not agree with Accused’s counsel that even if the range in _Cheng Jun_ was adopted, the sentence for the 28th Charge should be two months.

306    First, whilst I acknowledge that the transfer which is the subject of the 28th Charge was one to the Victim’s credit card account and went towards repaying the sums due on the Victim’s credit card account, this does not tell the entire story as far as the Accused’s culpability for the 28th Charge is concerned.

307    The transfer which was the subject matter of the 28th Charge took place on 15 July 2015 and went towards repaying amounts due on the Victim’s UOB Lady’s Classic card. As the Prosecution has pointed out, as of 15 July 2015, the majority of the amounts due on that card account stemmed from cash advances made by the Accused from the Victim’s UOB Lady’s Classic Card account in the month leading up to the 15 July 2015 transfer and fees related to those cash advances. Those cash advances are the subject of some of the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges.

308    Second, whilst the range of two to three months mentioned in _Cheng Jun_ is a useful starting point, I am of the view that this court is not necessarily constrained by the same, particularly when the specific precedents relied on in _Cheng Jun_ are not before this court.

309    In the premises, I imposed a sentence of four months’ imprisonment for the 28th Charge, to reflect the greater amount involved in the Charge when compared to the other CMA and Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges for which the Accused has been convicted. This was also consistent with the sentences meted out in _Hairul Faizal_ and _Biak Kim Sung._

### False Information Charge under section 203 Penal Code.

310    Section 203 of the PC provides that a person convicted under that section

> …shall be imprisonment for a term which may extend to 2 years, or with fine, or with both.

311    Prosecution submitted that the Accused’s conduct in relation to this Charge warranted the imposition of a two week imprisonment sentence.

312    On the part of the Accused, it was submitted that the circumstances here did not warrant the imposition of a custodial sentence and that a fine of $2,000 would suffice.

313    Counsel for the Accused pointed out that there are precedents involving section 177 PC offences where offenders were sentenced to a fine only. It was highlighted that in _Chua Wen Hao_, the High Court had imposed a fine, allegedly on the basis that the certain public resources wasted would have had to be incurred anyway and the offence was not premeditated nor carried out in a sophisticated manner.

314    Two unreported cases, being those of _PP v Ahmad Ghuzaili bin Ismail__[\[note: 77\]](#Ftn_77)_ (“**_Ahmad Ghuzaili bin Ismail_**_”)_ and _PP v Zailani bin Madnam[^78]_ (“**_Zailani bin Madnam_**”), were also cited in support of the Accused’s submission.

315    In my view, _Ahmad Ghuzaili bin Ismail_ and _Zailani bin Madnam_ do not give the entire picture.

316    To begin, _Ahmad Ghuzaili bin Ismail_ and _Zailani bin Madnam_ were only two of a number of decisions referred to by the court in _Chua Wen Hao_. A number of other decisions were also referred to by the court in _Chua Wen Hao_, some of which involved custodial sentences being imposed for convictions under section 177 of the PC.

317    For instance, another case considered in _Chua Wen Hao_ was _Public Prosecutor v Mugin Mariaras__[\[note: 79\]](#Ftn_79)_ (“**_Mugin Mariaras_**”), the accused was a police officer who falsely represented to his superior officer that no unclaimed lost-and-found property had been received at his Neighbourhood Police Post, although he had received a lost-and-found wallet. The accused in that case was sentenced to two weeks’ imprisonment.

318    The facts of _Mariaras_ might bear closer resemblance to the facts of the case before this court than those in _Ahmad Ghuzaili bin Ismail_ and _Zailani bin Madnam_, given that in _Mariaras_ and this case the accused persons gave false information about appropriating property not belonging to them, which was an element apparently not present in the cases of _Ahmad Ghuzaili bin Ismail_ and _Zailani bin Madnam._

319    Further, in _Koh Yong Chiah v PP__[\[note: 80\]](#Ftn_80) (“_**_Koh Yong Chiah_**_”)_, which was also referred to by counsel for the Accused in their written submissions, the High Court made observations about the sentences imposed in different types of cases in which false information might be provided (albeit in the context of section 182 of the PC).[^81]

320    One category of cases considered by the court in _Koh Yong Chiah_ was “cases where a person gave false information to the authorities to shield himself from investigation or prosecution”.[\[note: 82\]](#Ftn_82)

321    The High Court in _Koh Yong Chiah_ observed that in a number of cases brought under section 182 PC falling within this category, custodial sentences were imposed.[\[note: 83\]](#Ftn_83)

322    The court in _Koh Yong Chiah_ went on to comment that generally speaking, for section 182 offences,

> … whether the custodial threshold is crossed should essentially be determined based on the _degree of harm_ caused or likely to be caused by the s 182 offence. As the High Court in _CLB_ observed at \[9\], “the \[sentencing\] norm must be varied according to the circumstances of each case, in particular, _the mischief that might be caused by the false information_” \[emphasis added\]. Specifically, if _appreciable harm_ may be caused by the s 182 offence, the courts should, as a starting point, impose a custodial term. The range of harm that may ensue includes personal injury (eg, by causing another to contract HIV), loss of liberty (eg, by causing another to be unjustifiably arrested), **financial loss (eg, by lying to facilitate the misappropriation of property** or to commit insurance fraud) or harm arising from the wastage of public investigative resources.[\[note: 84\]](#Ftn_84)

> (Emphasis in bold added)

323    In addition, in _Chua Wen Hao_, the court endorsed the approach taken in _Koh Yong Chiah_, and also set out a non-exhaustive list of factors to be considered in sentencing for offences under section 177 of the PC:

> (a)    Offence-specific factors: (i) the complexity of the deceptive scheme employed to deceive the public servant concerned (for example, whether other persons were asked to corroborate the false information provided, and whether the offence was planned and premeditated or committed on the spur of the moment); (ii) **the seriousness of the predicate offence that the offender sought to conceal**; (iii) the extent to which public resources were wasted as a result of the false information provided; and (iv) the offender’s culpability (including his or her motive).

> (b)    Offender-specific factors: (i) the offender’s antecedents; (ii) the offender’s plea of guilt; and (iii) charges taken into consideration.[\[note: 85\]](#Ftn_85)

> (Emphasis added)

324    It was not argued before me that the guidance in _Koh Yong Chiah_ or _Chua Wen Hao_ should not apply to my consideration of the appropriate sentence to be imposed in relation to the False Information Charge. To the contrary, both the Prosecution and Defence cited _Chua Wen Hao_ in their submissions on sentence.

325    In my view, the Accused’s submission that the custodial threshold has not been crossed in this case fails to account for the seriousness of the predicate offences which he sought to conceal.

326    The Accused stands convicted of 52 other offences, all involving the misappropriation of property, including substantial amounts of money, from his then-girlfriend. These are the offences which the Accused sought to conceal by way of the false information he provided to the police.

327    Further, whilst is it true that in _Koh Yong Chiah_ the court did opine that “appreciable harm” was the threshold of the imposition of a custodial sentence, it did also observe that harm in this context refers to both actual and potential harm.[\[note: 86\]](#Ftn_86)

328    It bears noting that the Accused’s relationship with the Victim did not end on the night the police reports were lodged by the Victim and the Accused on 17 August 2015. At the trial, the Victim gave evidence that the relationship continued from August 2015 to February 2016 because she believed the Accused, who insisted he was not the culprit and that the money had been transferred by a friend of the Accused.[\[note: 87\]](#Ftn_87) The potential for the Accused to continue committing the predicate offences was therefore present for almost half a year following the making of the police report on 17 August 2015.

329    In view of the foregoing, and in light of the cases cited at \[24\] of the judgment in _Koh Yong Chiah_ and at \[41\] and \[42\] of _Chua Wen Hao_, I imposed a sentence of two weeks’ imprisonment on the Accused for the False Information Charge.

## Global sentence to be imposed

330    I set out below the reasons for the global sentence that was eventually imposed on the Accused.

331    Section 307(1) CPC requires me to order that at least two of the sentences I have imposed run consecutively.

### How individual sentences should run

332    The offences for which the Accused was convicted fall into the following categories:

> (a)     The Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges under section 379 of the PC;

> (b)     The Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges under section 3(1) of the CMA;

> (c)     Theft of the Stolen Cards; and

> (d)     One False Information Charge.

333    In my view, each of the above categories represented a separate invasion of a distinct legally protected interest.

334    To begin, the False Information Charge clearly stands apart from the other offences for which the Accused has been convicted, because the offence encompassed by this Charge was of a fundamentally different nature from those other Charges, which were in the nature of property offences.

335    As for each of the remaining three categories of Charges set out in \[332\] above, I appreciate that all of them involved property offences and occurred in close proximity of time, indeed during the same period.

336    That being said, in my view they should be regarded as invasions of separate legally protected interests because the means of and purpose (in the case of the Stolen Card Charges) for perpetrating the offences differed.

337    Specifically, whereas the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges were characterised as a direct misappropriation of the Victim’s financial resources, the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges impinged upon the security of the Victim’s electronic banking facilities, in addition to constituting the misappropriation of her property.

338    As for the offences encompassed by the Stolen Card Charges, these were effectively a prelude to the other offences for which the Accused was convicted. However, given that the Accused’s actions in misappropriating the Stolen Cards in and of themselves would have constituted offences regardless of whether he had used them to make unauthorised withdrawals, in my view, it would be appropriate to regard the Stolen Card Charges as a separate invasion of a distinct legally protected interest from the other property offences for which he was convicted.

339    Alternatively, and in any event, in _Mohamed Shouffee bin Adam_, it was pointed out that there might be instances where sentences are ordered to run consecutively even though they may be seen to relate to the same protected interest.[\[note: 88\]](#Ftn_88)

340    One example would be “where the straightforward application of the one-transaction rule results in the offender benefitting from the court’s failure to have regard to the enhanced culpability that is reflected in the multiplicity of the offences that have been committed.”[\[note: 89\]](#Ftn_89)

341    This is clearly the situation which this court is faced with on this occasion, as the Accused has been convicted on numerous counts of theft and CMA offences, where the amount involved in each individual Charge constituted generally to only a small proportion of the substantially larger aggregate sum that was misappropriated.

342    By reason of the foregoing, in order to reflect the Accused’s enhanced culpability in having committed multiple offences, in my view it was appropriate, in respect of the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges and the Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges, to order that the sentences for the three most egregious examples within each of these categories, measured by reference to the sums involved, should run consecutively. In my view, this would not be excessive, given that the Accused has been convicted of 27 Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges and 21 Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges.

343    For the Charges relating to the Stolen Cards, the sentence for one Charge was ordered to run consecutively. The sentence for the False Information Charge was also ordered to run consecutively.

344    The specific Charges which were ordered to run consecutively are highlighted in green and in bold in the sentencing table annexed to these Grounds.

345    The application of the foregoing resulted in a presumptive global sentence of 17 months and 8 weeks’ imprisonment.

### The totality principle

346    As the final stage of the sentencing analysis framework, I applied the totality principle to ensure that “the aggregate sentence is sufficient and proportionate to the offender’s overall criminality”.[\[note: 90\]](#Ftn_90)

347    In making their respective submissions on the global sentence to be applied in this case, both the Prosecution as well as counsel for the Accused sought to justify their proposed global sentences primarily by reference to the overall financial loss, suffered by the Victim, caused by the Accused acts under the Charges.

348    The Prosecution’s submission is that a global sentence of 21 months’ imprisonment would be appropriate in this case.

349    In support of this, the Prosecution referred to the case of _PP v Li Qichong_ (“**_Li Qichong_**”, unreported), wherein the Accused had stolen items such as laptops and mobile phones valued, in aggregate, at a sum of $19,063. The accused faced four charges under section 380 of the PC, three charges under section 379 of the PC and one charge under section 3(1) of the CMA, and pleaded guilty to three proceeded charges under section 380 of the PC and one proceeded charge under section 379 of the PC, with the remaining charges taken into consideration. He was sentenced to a total of 16 months’ imprisonment.

350    Prosecution highlighted that, in contrast to _Li Qichong_, in the present case the Accused claimed trial and also occasioned loss to his Victim of a significantly larger amount. This was so even though the Prosecution eventually accepted that the loss occasioned by the Accused to the Victim on this occasion ought not to include sums which were transferred from one of the Victim’s accounts into another account belonging to the Victim, because these transfers did not cause an immediate loss to the Victim.

351    In this regard, adding the sums involved in the Unauthorised Withdrawal Charges to the sums involved in those Unauthorised Fund Transfer Charges where the Accused had made transfers _to his own account_ gives $45,088. This is the _minimum_ amount which can appropriately be considered the loss occasioned by the Accused to the Victim. As highlighted by the Prosecution, the Accused’s usage of the account linked to the Victim’s UOB Cashplus Card also caused the Victim to incur further and separate interest charges of $137.80.[\[note: 91\]](#Ftn_91)

352    For the Accused, his counsel submitted on his behalf that an appropriate global sentence would be 12 months’ imprisonment. This submission was based on the decision in _R Balasubramiam_, in which the accused was sentenced to a total of 12 months’ imprisonment for misappropriating various sums amounting, in aggregate, to $128,962.

353    With respect, I do not think that the presumptive sentence I have arrived at above is disproportionate on account of _R Balasubramiam_. As highlighted earlier, there were significant mitigating factors present in that case which are absent here, the most significant being the fact that the accused in _R Balasubramaniam_ pleaded guilty and “clearly tried to make amends which was indicative of repentance”[\[note: 92\]](#Ftn_92).

354    In assessing the presumptive global sentence through the lens of the totality principle in this case, it bears emphasizing that the Accused was convicted of a substantial number of Charges. As such, even allowing for the principle that “an aggregation resulting in a longer sentence is going to carry a compounding effect that bears more than a linear relation to the cumulative and overall criminality of the case”,[\[note: 93\]](#Ftn_93) the global sentence imposed must reflect the multiple instances of offending present here.

355    For completeness, I would add that no information was placed before me to suggest that a global sentence of 17 months and 8 weeks’ imprisonment would be crushing on the Accused and not in keeping with his past record and future prospects.

356    As such, I preferred the Prosecution’s submissions as to what should amount to a limiting factor on the global sentence here when applying the totality principle. In this regard, given that the global sentence imposed in _Li Qichong_, in respect of offences involving a significantly lower amount ($19,063), an accused who pleaded guilty and who was facing fewer charges in any event, was already 16 months’ imprisonment, I consider that the presumptive sentence of 17 months and 8 weeks’ imprisonment would not offend the totality principle.

## Conclusion: Sentencing

357    In line with the foregoing, I imposed the individual sentences set out in the sentencing table accompanying these Grounds. Sentences which were ordered to run consecutively are highlighted in green and in bold in the same table.

358    The global sentence imposed on the Accused was 17 months’ and 8 weeks’ imprisonment.
